Intervention Planning
---------------------

Annie: I've been thinking about what happened originally. At first, Johnny was running away before my roommate could even get him up to his bedroom. When she tried positive reinforcement, it worked! She got him up to the bedroom. 

Annie: But when she told him to go to bed, he would laugh and run away, like it was a game. So what happened was that the original problem behavior -- refusing to go up to the bedroom -- was replaced by an alternative behavior -- laughing and running away from the bedroom.

JJ: Right. But both behaviors had the same function: Escape. Putting off bedtime.

Lin: That means even if your roommate finds a way to make sure he gets into bed, if she doesn't do anything different, he'll just come up with another alternative behavior. For example, he could ask for a bedtime story. And when that one's finished, he could ask for another one!

